test_endpoint.title: NASA to Provide Coverage of Preview Briefing, US Spacewalks
test_endpoint.summary: Astronauts aboard the International Space Station will conduct a series of U.S. spacewalks in November and December to install mounting hardware and a pair of rollout solar arrays to increase electrical power to support station operations and scientific research.

test_endpoint.title: NASA to Provide Live Coverage of US Spacewalks Outside Space Station
test_endpoint.summary: Astronauts aboard the International Space Station will conduct a pair of U.S. spacewalks in December to install rollout solar arrays to increase electrical power in support of station operations and scientific research.

test_endpoint.title: US spacewalk to install fourth iROSA completed after debris avoidance maneuver
test_endpoint.summary: Two NASA astronauts conducted a spacewalk outside the International Space Station (ISS) on Thursday, Dec. 22, to install a fourth new iROSA (ISS Roll-Out Solar Array). The Extra-Vehicular Activity (EVA) follows a previous one on Dec. 2 that installed the third iROSA.

test_endpoint.title: NASA postpones spacewalk to support Soyuz investigation
test_endpoint.summary: NASA is delaying a spacewalk at the International Space Station by two days to support the Russian investigation into a coolant leak on a Soyuz spacecraft docked there.

test_endpoint.title: NASA to Air Live Coverage of US Spacewalk for Solar Array Installation
test_endpoint.summary: NASA astronauts aboard the International Space Station will conduct a spacewalk on Wednesday, Dec. 21, to install a rollout solar array to increase electrical power in support of operations and scientific research.

test_endpoint.title: Astronauts unfurl fourth roll-out solar array outside International Space Station
test_endpoint.summary: Another roll-out solar array was installed and deployed by astronauts Frank Rubio and Josh Cassada outside the International Space Station on on a spacewalk Thursday, a day later than previously planned after the space station needed to dodge a piece of space junk.

Europe’s Jupiter-bound JUICE spacecraft is ready for April launch
test_endpoint.summary: The satellite behind Europe’s next flagship space mission is ready to be sent to French Guiana for an April launch to explore three of Jupiter’s largest icy moons, manufacturer Airbus announced Jan. 20.

test_endpoint.title: JUICE arrives in French Guiana for launch, project manager outlines next steps
test_endpoint.summary: Set for launch from the Centre Spatial Guyanais (CSG) in Kourou, French Guiana, on April 13, 2023, the European Space Agency’s (ESA’s) Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission will aim to uncover the secrets of Jupiter’s three largest icy moons: Ganymede, Callisto, and Europa. JUICE’s suite of instruments will allow scientists to thoroughly explore and characterize the moons, each of which is thought to feature large bodies of liquid water beneath their surfaces — creating potentially habitable environments for life.

test_endpoint.title: As launch approaches, JUICE project manager discusses trajectories and science
test_endpoint.summary: The European Space Agency’s (ESA) Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) spacecraft recently arrived in French Guiana for its upcoming launch, which is currently set for April 13, 2023. JUICE is currently undergoing launch preparations in the Payload Preparation Facility at the Centre Spatial Guyanais (CSG) in Kourou, French Guiana, and will soon be mounted atop the upper stage of the Ariane 5 rocket it will ride into orbit.

test_endpoint.title: Ariane 5 ready to launch ESA’s JUICE mission to Jupiter
test_endpoint.summary: Europe’s first mission to Jupiter is ready to launch on the next to last flight of the Ariane 5 on April 13.

test_endpoint.title: ESA launches JUICE to Jupiter’s icy moons atop Ariane 5
test_endpoint.summary: European Space Agency (ESA) and Arianespace teams have conducted the launch of the historic Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission to the three largest icy moons of Jupiter — Ganymede, Callisto, and Europa. The launch, dubbed Flight VA260, is the first of two Ariane 5 missions of 2023 and the penultimate flight of the Ariane 5 rocket, lofting JUICE on a trajectory that will result in a summer 2031 arrival and orbit insertion at the Jovian system.

test_endpoint.title: Europe successfully launches spacecraft toward the moons of Jupiter [Updated]
test_endpoint.summary: "We wanted to see if these were possible habitats for life."

test_endpoint.title: ESA Launches Europe's First Mission to Jupiter
test_endpoint.summary: The ESA Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission is now on its way to Jupiter after its successful launch onboard an Ariane 5 rocket from Europe's Spaceport in French Guiana, this 5,963kg satellite is tasked with exploring the gas giant Jupiter and its Icey moons. The mission is expected to take around 8 years to get to Jupiter.

test_endpoint.title: Ariane 5 launches ESA’s JUICE mission to Jupiter
test_endpoint.summary: An Ariane 5 successfully launched a European spacecraft on an eight-year journey to Jupiter April 14 on the penultimate flight of the venerable rocket.

test_endpoint.title: Europe’s major new interplanetary spacecraft has a slight problem
test_endpoint.summary: Various options are still available to nudge the important instrument.

test_endpoint.title: As JUICE struggles with antenna deployment, program manager highlights status of the mission
test_endpoint.summary: The European Space Agency’s (ESA) latest interplanetary mission that is set to explore Jupiter and its three largest Moons, the Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE), successfully launched on Friday, April 14, has been touted as a near-perfect feat. JUICE had little-to-no issues during the launch sequence, right from blasting off atop an Ariane 5 rocket from the Centre Spatial Guyanais (CSG) in Kourou, French Guiana within a one-second launch window, to deploying its massive solar arrays.

test_endpoint.title: ESA troubleshooting JUICE radar antenna
test_endpoint.summary: A radar antenna on a European mission to Jupiter has yet to fully deploy after launch, although project officials say they still have plenty of options to fix the problem.

test_endpoint.title: JUICE deploys radar antenna
test_endpoint.summary: A radar antenna on a newly-launched European mission to Jupiter has finally deployed after weeks of effort to loosen a stuck pin.

test_endpoint.title: JUICE Successfully Deploys Radar Antenna
test_endpoint.summary: In a triumph of engineering persistence, the radar antenna on the Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission, a European Space Agency (ESA) venture, has finally deployed after being stuck for weeks.
